full_text:
Thanks for the info, Bruce.  I guess because I use such a wide variety of digital recorders, 
techniques, software, and settings, what I&#39;m looking for is a way to catalog the session 
clips along with the details.  This is not counting the MiniBox, 12-469, 12-470, either of 
my manual sweep radios, or EVP Maker.  So, like yourself, I too have much more than &quot;one 
box&quot; to keep track of.   I also have a variety of cameras/settings used for ITC images.  LOL 
- I&#39;m in definite need of something &quot;fancy.&quot;  ;0)

If I can recall what the file is named, I can use the &quot;spotlight&quot; feature on my MAC to find it, 
though often the content of  a single file is much longer than I could possible name it.  For 
example, my recent results with EVP Maker/SpeakJet Allophones.  I do jot some things 
down in a Mead notebook, but even that can be a chore to go through when I&#39;m wanting to 
find information that is older.

For example, without electronic organization, I can pull up a file and recall that I used 
Diamond Cut Live6/Forensics software, but if I can&#39;t refer to some kind of notes, there is 
no way I can recall what the specific settings were unless the session was recent and still 
fresh in my mind (and/or the notes easily found.)

What I&#39;m wanting is some kind of simple database.  It&#39;s looking more and more like I&#39;m just 
going to have to buy the software and create it.  If I do, I&#39;ll be sure to share the template 
with others who might also be interested.

Margaret

--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, bruce halliday &lt;paranormalinvestigating@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; hi Margaret,
&gt;  
&gt; I just use a folder dedicated to the individual session 
&gt; whatever files I get go in, numbered in the order I got them from the recording.
&gt;  
&gt; The main recording file gets named with the box used, date and session # if you use 
one.
&gt;  
&gt; these individual session folders are placed into a main folder, or you could create sub 
folders for each
&gt; month and place those in a main folder.
&gt;  
&gt; I don&#39;t think you need anything fancy, especially since you are only using one box.
&gt; I use 5 different boxes and now EVPM so for me it could really get confusing.
&gt;  
&gt; for you the simpler the better. If it&#39;s something like this
&gt;  
&gt; Main folder: box files/2008
&gt;  
&gt; sub folders1: jan., feb., mar. so forth.
&gt;  
&gt; sub folders2: 469_session5_3-31-08
&gt; All files including main go into sub folders2
&gt; in turn that folder goes into the appropriate sub folder1
&gt; when the month is over that sub folder goes into the folder for the year.
&gt;  
&gt; Say you wanted to reference a file from 3-31-08, you would know exactly were to find 
it.
&gt;  
&gt; that&#39;s how I do it and it seems to work.
&gt;  
&gt; bruce
